The nonprofit Life360 Community Services plans to provide snacks every school day to every in-person student at Reeds Spring Schools. Examples of snacks include fruits and vegetables, crackers, cheese, and milk. Funding for the program comes from the United States Department of Agriculture.

The program may begin on different days in the different buildings throughout the district. The administrator in each building will determine when the snacks will be distributed.

We are grateful to Life360 Community Services for this generous offering to our students.

post_text:
The Stone County Health Department has advised Reeds Spring Schools to limit large gatherings due to health concerns. As a result, the district will reduce the number of people allowed to attend varsity football games.

All RSHS students participating in the game festivities (players, cheerleaders, band members, etc‚Ä¶) will receive four tickets to distribute to family and friends. In addition, 50 tickets will be available to RSHS students through a weekly lottery. Students must enter their names in the lottery each week through a link that will be shared by the school. Each visiting school will receive 300 tickets to distribute to its fans.

Admission will still be paid at the gate, but you must have a ticket to enter the stadium. Face coverings will be required for all spectators.

The RSHS Media Team plans to live stream football games on YouTube, so fans who do not have tickets can still enjoy Wolves football.

#ONEwiththePACK

The Reeds Spring School District‚Äôs Back-to-School Plan is linked below. We believe establishing a safe environment is essential and our decisions have been based on what is best for students.

Please know that district leaders care deeply for your children and have poured many hours of research and energy into creating this plan. We know that collaboration of all stakeholders is important, and that‚Äôs why this plan incorporates elements from our family and staff surveys.

post_text: Congratulations to these three RSHS students for earning dual-credit scholarships from the School Foundation! #ONEwiththePACK
shared_text:
Reeds Spring Pack Night at Dolly Parton's Stampede
May 2 at 8:59 AM ¬∑

The Reeds Spring School Foundation has awarded $250 scholarships to three high school students to help offset the costs of dual-credit courses.

Congratulations to RSHS students Loric Arnold, Brooke Davis, and Jacqueline Durant.

Dual-credit courses allow students to earn both high school and college credits. This gives students a head start on college and helps save them money because dual-credit courses at Reeds Spring High School cost much less than at a college.

Reeds Spring High School offers nearly 20 dual-credit courses, which add up to more than 50 hours of college credits.

The Reeds Spring School Foundation will award more scholarships in August. The money comes from the organization‚Äôs annual fundraiser, PACK NIGHT at Dolly Parton‚Äôs Stampede.

ùêëùêûùê≠ùê´ùê¢ùêûùêØùêöùê• ùê®ùêü ùêèùêûùê´ùê¨ùê®ùêßùêöùê• ùêÅùêûùê•ùê®ùêßùê†ùê¢ùêßùê†ùê¨

The district is offering families the opportunity to retrieve any personal belongings that students still have inside of our buildings. This will occur on Monday, April 27 and Wednesday, April 29. The times are from 10:30 a.m. - 12:00 p.m. and 5:00 - 6:30 p.m.

For grades K-6, staff members have placed all student belongings in bags and they will be handed out in a drive-through line at each building. We also ask that you please return all library books at this time.

For grades 7-12, students may enter the building to clean out their lockers. They must first check-in at the front office. We will only allow a small number of students to enter at one time.

If you are unable to visit the schools during any of the times listed above, we will offer another opportunity at some point in the summer.

#ONEwiththePACK

Our Employee of the Month for March is Intermediate School nurse Angie Clamors!

‚ÄúNurse Angie is constantly encouraging staff and students to prioritize their health,‚Äù said principal Andrea Chavez. ‚ÄúShe finds fun and engaging ways to keep students motivated to sanitize and wash their hands.‚Äù

Clamors has worked for the school district for two years. Students and staff appreciate her positive attitude and ability to encourage everyone to make health a priority.

‚ÄúNurse Angie is quick to take the initiative in any way needed, and she is always a team player,‚Äù Chavez said. #ONEwiththePACK

post_text: The Reeds Spring School District will continue its supplemental learning program through May 15 and our food distribution program will also continue. #ONEwiththePACK
shared_text:
Governor Mike Parson
April 9 at 2:56 PM ¬∑

We are ordering all Missouri public and charter schools to remain closed through the remainder of the academic year with the exceptions of nutrition services and child care that are outlined in our recent health order.

This recommendation was made by working together with the Missouri Department of Elementary and Secondary Education and several school superintendents from across the state -- from both urban and rural districts.

Schools should continue remote learning for their students until the end date previously set on their academic calendars.

On Friday, April 10 at 8:20 p.m., we will turn on the lights at the football field and baseball field to show support for the Class of 2020 and spring athletes, coaches, and families.

The lights will be a symbol, showing that we are thinking of them and that eventually, we will return to school and competition.

The lights will be on for 20 minutes, starting at 8:20 p.m. You are invited to drive past the fields and honk your horns. Please remain in your vehicles in order to adhere to physical distancing guidelines.
#ONEwiththePACK

The lights will be a symbol, showing that we are thinking of them and that eventually, we will return to school and competition.

The lights will be on for 20 minutes, starting at 8:20 p.m. You are invited to drive past the fields and honk your horns. Please remain in your vehicles in order to adhere to physical distancing guidelines.
#ONEwiththePACK

We are making an adjustment to our meal distribution program starting on Monday, March 30. To ease the burden on families driving to get meals each day, we will begin serving the meals only on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays. We will hand out two days worth of meals at a time, so we are providing the same amount of food.

The times remain the same: 10:00 a.m. - 12:00 p.m. at Reeds Spring Middle School, and 10:30 a.m. - 11:30 a.m. at our remote locations, which are the Kimberling City Shopping Center, Indian Point Chamber of Commerce, and Cape Fair Eagles Lodge.

Also, we want to get an accurate count of how many people still need this service, so we are asking that you please register again. The sign-up form can be found on the link below, or you may also sign-up over the phone by calling 417-248-7008.
#ONEwiththePACK

This program will be available Monday through Friday starting on March 23 from 10:00 a.m. to 12:00 p.m. at Reeds Spring Middle School. Please use the event entrance at the bottom of the hill. We will also have distribution locations at the Cape Fair Eagles Lodge, Indian Point Chamber of Commerce, and Kimberling City Shopping Center from 10:30-11:30 a.m. Each child will receive one lunch meal for that day and one breakfast meal for the following day.

A sign-up form link can be found at the bottom of this message so we can have an idea of how many meals to prepare. If you know someone who does not have internet service, please tell them to call 417-248-7008 and leave their information on the voice mail.

Students who would like to be Reeds Spring Middle School cheerleaders during the 2020-2021 school year should plan to attend tryouts on March 30-April 2 from 3:45-6:00 p.m. in the Primary School gym.

The first three days will be a clinic and the fourth day will be tryouts. This is open to next year's seventh and eighth-graders. Students must have a physical on file with the middle school or they can bring one to the first day of the clinic. Students cannot participate without a physical.

Cheerleaders perform during both football and basketball seasons.

post_text:
The Reeds Spring School District helped to feed nearly 80 families through its annual food drive. Each building in the district collected food throughout November. Collection boxes were also set up at Oakley Auto World, Lakeview Learning Center, and Harter House.

District staff members contributed money in exchange for being allowed to wear jeans all month. That brought in nearly $2,000, which was used to provide perishable foods, like burgers, chicken, and hot dogs.

The district also accepted donations during Trunk or Treat in October, and that money was used to buy a ham for each of the families in need.

Reeds Spring High School students gathered and handed out shoes and coats, in addition to helping sort, box, and hand out all of the food. #ONEwiththePACK
